'''''Iris sibirica''''' is a species in the genus ''[[Iris (plant)|Iris]]'', it is also in the subgenus of [[Iris subg. Limniris|Limniris]]'' and series of ''[[Iris series Sibiricae]]''. It is a [[rhizomatous]] [[herbaceous plant|herbaceous]] [[perennial plant|perennial]].

Iris sibirica is pronounced as ''EYE-ris sy-BEER-ah-kuh''.<ref name=daves>{{cite web |title=PlantFiles: Siberian Iris |url=http://davesgarden.com/guides/pf/go/880/#b |publisher=davesgarden.com |accessdate=3 January 2015}}</ref>

It has the common names of ''Siberian Iris'',<ref name=landscape>{{cite web |title=Iris |date=13 February 2010 |url=http://rslandscapedesign.blogspot.co.uk/2010/02/hollies-new-improved-re-edited-repost.html |publisher=rslandscapedesign.blogspot.co.uk |accessdate=19 December 2014}}</ref><ref name=kew>{{cite web |title=Iris sibirica (Siberian iris) |url=http://www.kew.org/science-conservation/plants-fungi/iris-sibirica-siberian-iris |publisher=kew.org |accessdate=3 January 2015}}</ref><ref name=bbc>{{cite web |title=Siberian iris |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/gardening/plants/plant_finder/plant_pages/9009.shtml |publisher=bbc.co.uk |accessdate=3 January 2015}}</ref><ref name=grin>{{cite web |title=Taxon: Iris sibirica L. |date=1 December 2004 |url=http://www.ars-grin.gov/cgi-bin/npgs/html/taxon.pl?20398 |publisher=ars-grin.gov ([[Germplasm Resources Information Network]])  |accessdate=3 January 2015}}</ref><ref name=signa>{{cite web |first=D. |last=Kramb |date=2 October 2004 |title=Iris sibirica |url=http://www.signa.org/index.pl?Iris-sibirica |publisher=signa.org (Species Iris Group of North America) |accessdate=3 January 2015}}</ref><ref name=eflora>{{cite web |title=FNA Vol. 26 Page 373, 382 |url=http://www.efloras.org/florataxon.aspx?flora_id=1&taxon_id=200028213 |publisher=efloras.org (Flora of North America) |accessdate=3 January 2015}}</ref><ref name=cold>Mike Heger, John Whitman and Debbie Lonnee {{Google books|Growing Perennials in Cold Climates|l_Ftvdh539MC|page=227}}</ref> or ''Siberian Flag'' (mainly in the UK).<ref name=rhs>{{cite web |title=Iris sibirica  |url=https://www.rhs.org.uk/plants/details?plantid=6230 |publisher=rhs.org.uk  |accessdate=3 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Siberian Flag Iris sibirica - 1L Pot |url=http://www.primrose.co.uk/siberian-flag-iiris-sibiricai-pot-p-66865.html |publisher=primrose.co.uk |accessdate=5 January 2015}}</ref>

It is known as ''iris de Sib<U+00E9>rie'' (in French), ''sibirische Schwertlilie'' or ''Wiesen-Schwertlilie'' (in German) and ''strandiris'' (in Swedish).<ref name=grin/>

It has been around before the 1500s and was first called ''Iris augustifolia media'' by [[Carolus Clusius]].<ref name=stebbings>{{cite book |last=Stebbings |first=Geoff |year=1997|title=The Gardener's Guide to Growing Irises |url= |location=Newton Abbot |publisher=David and Charles |page=45 |isbn=0715305395 }}</ref> It was first collected in Siberia by [[monks]] in the Middle Ages and grown in [[monasteries]], later it was distributed around Europe,where there are now many cultivars.<ref name=bristol>{{cite web |title=Summer picks up the pace! |date=11 June 2012 |url=http://www.bristol.ac.uk/botanic-garden/news/2012/21.html publisher=bristol.ac.uk |accessdate=3 January 2015}}</ref> It has been cultivated in Britain since 1596.<ref name=plantatlas>{{cite web |title=Iris sibirica (Siberian Iris) |url=http://www.brc.ac.uk/plantatlas/index.php?q=node/4018 |publisher=brc.ac.uk |accessdate=3 January 2015}}</ref>

It was then first described and published by [[Carl Linnaeus]] in his book, ''Species Plantarum'' 1 39 on 1 May 1753.<ref>{{cite web |title=Iridaceae Iris sibirica L. |url=http://www.ipni.org/ipni/idPlantNameSearch.do?id=439087-1 |publisher=ipni.org ([[International Plant Names Index]]) |accessdate=13 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Caroli Linnaei ... Species plantarum :exhibentes plantas rite cognitas, ad genera relatas, cum differ |url=http://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/358060 |publisher=biodiversitylibrary.org |accessdate=13 December 2014}}</ref> Who renamed  the iris, ''Iris sibirica''.<ref name=stebbings/>

It was verified by [[United States Department of Agriculture]] [[Agricultural Research Service]] on 20 April 1998.<ref name=grin/>

The [[NCCPG National Plant Collection|National Collection]] (of Siberian Irises in UK) is held at Lingen Nursery, on the Welsh border.<ref name=countryfile>{{cite web |title=Splendours of Iris sibirica |date=25 May 2006 |url=http://www.countrylife.co.uk/gardens/gardening-tips/splendours-of-irish-sibirica#xLOpqJlj5c4OJMRg.99 |publisher=countrylife.co.uk |accessdate=3 January 2015}}</ref>

An illustration of iris sibirica has been used as a [[Postage stamp]] in [[Poland]].<ref name=stamp>{{cite web |title=Postage stamp Poland 1967 Iris Sibirica, Medical Plant |url=http://www.bigstockphoto.com/image-34970720/stock-photo-postage-stamp-poland-1967-iris-sibirica,-medical-plant |publisher=bigstockphoto.com |accessdate=3 January 2015}}</ref>

[[Johan Peter Falk]] noted that the Tara [[Tartars]] of Russia (West Siberia) coloured cloth yellow with ''Iris sibirica'' flowers and the [[Votyaks]], [[Mordvins]] and [[Kalmyks]] derived red dye from [[Galium]] species.<ref>David Philip Miller and Peter Hanns Reill (Editors){{Google books|Visions of Empire: Voyages, Botany, and Representations of Nature (1996)|y6SJia-cSnQC|page=130}}</ref>
In 2014, it was tested for its potential to be used for dying.<ref name=dyingpotential>{{cite journal |last=Ka<U+0161><U+0161><U+00E1>k |first=Pavol |last2=Kuli |first2=Magdalena |date=September 2014 |title=DYEING POTENTIAL OF THE IRIS SIBIRICA L. FLOWERS |url=http://eujournal.org/index.php/esj/article/download/4163/3999. |journal=European Scientific Journal |volume=2  |pages=372<U+2013>380  |accessdate=3 January 2015}}</ref>

Like many other irises, most parts of the plant are poisonous (rhizome and leaves), if mistakenly ingested can cause stomach pains and vomiting. Also handling the plant may cause a skin irritation or an allergic reaction.<ref name=daves/><ref name=kew/> Although an edible [[starch]] has been extracted from the plant in China, similar to [[Iris ensata]].<ref>{{cite web |editor-last=Hedrick |editor-first=U.P. |title=Edible plants of the world |url= http://www.swsbm.com/Ephemera/Sturtevants_Edible_Plants.pdf  |format=PDF |page=360 |publisher=swsbm.com |accessdate=3 January 2015}}</ref> The root has also been used to create an [[insecticide]] and an [[expectorant]].<ref name=natural>{{cite web |title=Herb: Siberian Iris |url=http://www.naturalmedicinalherbs.net/herbs/i/iris-sibirica=siberian-iris.php |publisher=naturalmedicinalherbs.net |accessdate=3 January 2015}}</ref>

An old traditional usage before the wedding night, [[Poles|Polish]] girls eat the cooked fruit (seeds) of Iris sibirica to help improve [[contraception]].<ref>Hermann Heinrich Ploss, Max Bartels and Paul Bartel{{Google books|Woman: An Historical Gyn<U+00E6>cological and Anthropological Compendium (1935)|_yW0BQAAQBAJ|page=300}}</ref><ref>Raymond W. Bernard{{Google books|The Mysteries of Human Reproduction|thbvifQ5DhwC|page=21}}</ref>

It has also been used to create a drug to be used as an [[emetic]] and [[laxative]].<ref name=cassidy>{{cite book |last1=Cassidy |first1=George E.| last2=Linnegar | first2=Sidney | date=1987 |edition=Revised  | title= Growing Irises  |location=Bromley | publisher=Christopher Helm | isbn=0-88192-089-4}}</ref>

It has been studied various times.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Stani<U+0161>i<U+0107>a |first=M. |last2=Raspora |first2=M. |last3=Ninkovi<U+0107>a |first3=S. |last4=Milo<U+0161>evi<U+0107>a |first4=S. |last5=<U+0106>ali<U+0107>a |first5=D. |last6=Bohanecb |first6=B. |last7=Trifunovi<U+0107>a |first7=M. |last8= Petri<U+0107>a |first8=M. |last9=Suboti<U+0107>a |first9=A. |last10=Jevremovi<U+0107>a |first10=S. |date=9 September 2014 |title=Clonal fidelity of Iris sibirica plants regenerated by somatic embryogenesis and organogenesis in leaf-base culture <U+2014> RAPD and flow cytometer analyses |url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S025462991400194X |journal=South African Journal of Botany |volume=96  |pages=42<U+2013>52 |accessdate=3 January 2015}}</ref><ref name=poland>{{cite journal |last=Kostrakiewicz |first=Kinga |last2=Wr<U+00F3>blewska |first2=Ada  |date=2 May 2007 |title=Low genetic variation in subpopulations of an endangered clonal plant Iris sibirica in southern Poland |url=http://www.jstor.org/stable/23727724 |journal=Annales Botanici Fennici |publisher=Finnish Zoological and Botanical Publishing Board |volume=45 |issue=3 (2008) |pages=186<U+2013>194  |accessdate=7 November 2014}}</ref><ref name=germanica>{{cite journal |last=Meyer |first=Chris J. |last2=Seago Jr |first2=James L. |last3=Peterson |first3=Carol A.  |date= |title=Environmental effects on the maturation of the endodermis and multiseriate exodermis of Iris germanica roots |url=http://www.aob.oxfordjournals.org |journal=Annals of Botany |publisher= |volume= |issue= |pages= |doi= 10.1093/aob/mcn255 |accessdate=3 January 2015}}</ref><ref name=pseudacorus>{{cite journal |last=Gontova |first=T. N. |last2=Zatylnikova |first2=O. A. |date=12 June 2013 |title=Comparative morphological and anatomical study of leaves and stems of Iris pseudacorus and iris sibirica |url=http://www.ijppsjournal.com/Vol5Suppl3/7401.pdf |format=PDF |journal=International Journal of Pharmacy and Pharmaceutical Sciences |publisher=National University of Pharmacy |volume=5 |accessdate=3 January 2015}}</ref>

As most irises are [[diploid]], having two sets of [[chromosomes]]. This can be used to identify hybrids and classification of groupings.<ref name=ClaireAustin>{{cite web| first=Claire | last=Austin | title=Irises A Garden Encyclopedia| pages=274<U+2013>275 | url=https://worldtracker.org/media/library/Reference/Encyclopedia's/Encyclopedia%20of%20Irises.pdf |format=PDF |publisher=worldtracker.org |accessdate=29 October 2014}}</ref>
It has been count various times; 2n=28, Sim. 1928; 2n=28, Skalinska, 1961; 2n=28, Wcislo, 1964; 2n=28 Baerji, 1970; 2n=28, Sharma, 1970; 2n=28; Lovka & Sus. 1971; 2n=28, Pop.& Cesch. 1975,1976; 2n=28, Wetschnig, 1988; 2n=28, Malakhova & Markova, 1994.<ref name=american>{{cite web |first=Terry |last=Laurin |title=(SPEC) Iris sibirica L. |date=9 October 2014 |url=http://wiki.irises.org/bin/view/Spec/SpecSibirica |publisher=wiki.irises.org  (American Iris Society) |accessdate=27 December 2014}}</ref>
2n=28 is the most common listed count.<ref name=signa/><ref name=eflora/><ref name=pacificsummary>{{cite web| title=Iris summary |date=14 April 2014 |url=http://www.pacificbulbsociety.org/pbswiki/files/Iris/Iris_Summary.pdf |format=pdf |publisher=pacificbulbsociety.org |accessdate=23 November 2014}}</ref>

This means it is similar to ''[[Iris sanguinea]]'' and ''[[Iris typhifolia]]''.<ref name=ClaireAustin/>

==Cultivation==
Generally the 28 chromosome hybrids are easier to grow than the Sino-Siberians.<ref name=bbc/><ref name=ClaireAustin/><ref name=sissinghurst>{{cite web |title=IRIS SIBIRICA: THE ELEGANT IRIS |date=5 June 2014  |url=http://sissinghurstcastle.wordpress.com/2014/06/05/iris-sibirica-the-elegant-iris/ |publisher=sissinghurstcastle.wordpress.com |accessdate=19 December 2014}}</ref>

It will tolerate temperatures down to -20&nbsp;<U+00B0>C (-30&nbsp;<U+00B0>F).<ref name=daves/><ref name=cold/><ref name=dyingpotential/><ref name=perennials>{{cite book |first1=Roger |last1=Phillips |first2=Martyn |last2=Rix |title=Perennials Vol. 1 |page=223 |year=1991 |publisher=Pan Books Ltd. |isbn=9780330327749}}</ref> It is [[Hardiness (plants)|hardy]] to [[USDA]] Zone 2-8,<ref name=daves/><ref name=eflora/><ref name=eflora/> and Zone H1 (which means hardy to -20oC and below (-4oF) <ref>{{cite web |title=Plant Hardiness  |url=http://theseedsite.co.uk/hardiness.html  |publisher=theseedsite.co.uk |accessdate=20 December 2014}}</ref>), in Europe.<ref name=European>James Cullen, Sabina G. Knees, H. Suzanne Cubey (Editors) {{Google books|CkxWrDqtWLQC|The European Garden Flora Flowering Plants: A Manual for the Identification|page=252}}</ref> It is hardy in the UK.<ref name=bbc/><ref name=rhs/> If the plants are mulched in winter they can withstand colder temperatures.<ref name=dyingpotential/>

The iris should be grown in well-drained,<ref name=bbc/><ref name=perennials/> fertile,<ref name=landscape/> neutral to slightly acidic soils (the [[pH level]] should be more than 5.6).<ref name=daves/><ref name=bbc/><ref name=parkes>{{cite web |first=Pat |last=Parkes |title=Siberian Iris |url=http://bc-iris.org/iris%20articles/Article-Siberian%20Iris. |publisher=htmbc-iris.org |accessdate=19 December 2014}}</ref><ref name=growing>{{cite web |first=John |last=Coble |title=Growing Siberian Iris |date=January 2014 |url=http://www.cdn-iris.ca/pdfs/growingsiberianiris.pdf  |format=PDF  |publisher=cdn-iris.ca |accessdate=3 January 2015}}</ref>

If the soil has a high sand or clay content, large amounts of organic material (such as compost or well rotted manure) should be incorporated at planting time.<ref name=parkes/><ref name=dailymail>{{cite news |first=Constance |last=Craig Smith |title=Russian revolution: Savvy gardeners are switching to Siberian irises for guaranteed late spring colour whatever the weather |date=13 April 2012 |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/home/gardening/article-2128779/Russian-revolution-Savvy-gardeners-switching-Siberian-irises-guaranteed-late-spring-colour-weather.html  |publisher=dailymail.co.uk ([[Daily Mail]]) |accessdate=3 January 2015}}</ref>

It prefers positions in full sun,<ref name=daves/><ref name=bbc/> but can tolerate part shade (with some hours of sunlight).<ref name=daves/><ref name=landscape/><ref name=bbc/><ref name="sissinghurst"/><ref name=parkes/><ref name=growing/><ref name=dailymail/> In very hot, arid regions, they will need some shade, as well as watering and mulching.<ref name=parkes/><ref name=growing/>

The plant needs moisture during the growing season (in spring and early summer) to create the best blooms.<ref name=daves/><ref name=bbc/> But they don't grow in the water.  Although they will tolerate occasional flooding.<ref name=landscape/><ref name=dyingpotential/><ref name=sissinghurst/><ref name=perennials/><ref name=parkes/>

As [[Vita Sackville West]] noted <U+2018><U+2026>it will do well by the waterside in a fairly damp bed, although it does not like being drowned underwater all year round.<U+2019><ref name=sissinghurst/>

They can be used in various positions within gardens, at waterside locations beside pools, ponds or streams.<ref name=bbc/><ref name=sissinghurst/>  Also known as ideal [[bog garden]] plants.<ref name=bbc/><ref name=dyingpotential/><ref name=sissinghurst/><ref name=dailymail/> They can also be used within a [[Herbaceous border]].<ref name=bbc/><ref name=dailymail/> The iris can also be used in mixed plantings with grasses and other perennials to create naturalized gardens and meadows.<ref name=parkes/>

They are sturdy plants and do not need to be staked.<ref name=landscape/>

==Propagation==
[[File:Iris sibirica MHNT.BOT.2009.7.17.jpg|thumb|seeds of Iris from the [[Mus<U+00E9>um de Toulouse]]]]
They are best propagated by [[Division (horticulture)|division]].<ref name=daves/><ref name=dailymail/><ref name=pacific>{{cite web |title=Beardless Irises Three |date=April 13, 2013  |url=http://pacificbulbsociety.org/pbswiki/index.php/BeardlessIrisesThree |publisher=pacificbulbsociety.org |accessdate=3 January 2015}}</ref> The best time to divide plants is mid-summer to early autumn.<ref name=bbc/> They do not like root disturbance and should only be divided when the center of the clump dies out.<ref name=landscape/> When preparing divisions for transplanting, store them in a bucket of water to stop them drying out.<ref name=parkes/>

The new plants are easy to grow but are slow to form flower producing plants, they can take up to 2 years to get big enough to produce flowering stems.<ref name=landscape/><ref name=dailymail/>

The iris can also be grown from seed, allow the mature pods to dry on the plant. Then break open to collect seeds and the direct sow outdoors in fall or autumn.<ref name=daves/><ref name=pacific/>

The new plants are planted with the top of the rhizome, 3<U+2013>5&nbsp;cm 1-2 inches below the soil surface.<ref name=landscape/> The plant position must be prepared before hand with plenty of compost (or manure) added to the soil to improve the fertility. After planting, the iris must be well watered.<ref name=dailymail/><ref name=knowhow>{{cite web |first=Becca |last=Badgett |title=Siberian Iris Care: Information On When To Plant Siberian Iris And Its Care |url=http://www.gardeningknowhow.com/ornamental/flowers/iris/growing-siberian-iris.htm |publisher=gardeningknowhow.com |accessdate=3 January 2015}}</ref> Seedlings are also susceptible to transplant shock, this can be lessened if a small plastic pot is placed over the newly planted plant. This protects the plant for the next 3<U+2013>5 days.<ref name=parkes/> In some regions (especially warm areas), the transplants should be kept moist for the following 6<U+2013>8 weeks.<ref name=growing/>

In spring, a hand full of [[fertilizer]] can be added to the plant to improve flowering or an organic mulch can be added.<ref name=parkes/><ref name=knowhow/>

==Description==
[[File:Iris Purple Top View 1788px.jpg|thumb|close-up of flower with water droplets]]
Iris sibirica was often confused with ''Iris sanguinea'', another blue flowering Asian iris.<ref name=handbook>{{cite web| first=William | last=Dykes| title=Handbook of Garden Irises | year=2009| url=http://www.beardlessiris.org/reviews/handbook%20of%20garden%20irises%20-%20dykes.pdf |format=pdf |  publisher=beardlessiris.org (The Group for Beardless Irises) | accessdate=1 November 2014}}</ref> But sanguinea has unbranched stems, while sibirica has branched stems.<ref name=stebbings/>

It has creeping rhizome (approximately {{convert|0.9|<U+2013>|1.2|cm|0|abbr=on}} diameter), forming a dense clumping plant.<ref name=landscape/><ref name=eflora/><ref name=perennials/><ref name=Lynch>Richard Lynch {{Google books|grvYTul5CSUC|The Book of the Iris|page=70}}</ref><ref name=russia>{{cite web|first=V.L. | last=Komarov | year=1935 | title=Akademiya Nauk SSSR (FLORA of the U.S.S.R.) Vol. IV | publisher=archive.org | url=http://archive.org/stream/floraofussr04bota/floraofussr04bota_djvu.txt |accessdate=9 October 2014}}</ref> The rhizomes are covered with the brown remnants of old leaves, from previous seasons.<ref name=eflora/><ref name=russia/>

It has green grass-like leaves,<ref name=cold/><ref name=rhs/><ref name=handbook/> which are ribbed and can sometimes have a pink tinge at the base of the leaf.<ref name=eflora/><ref name=perennials/>
They can grow to between {{convert|25|-|80|cm|0|abbr=on}} long and {{convert|0.4|-|0.6|cm|0|abbr=on}} wide, normally shorter then the flowering stems.<ref name=landscape/><ref name=eflora/><ref name=stebbings/><ref name=perennials/><ref name=European/><ref name=russia/>
In Autumn, the foliage turns yellow and then dies back (in winter), to re-emerge in the spring.<ref name=landscape/><ref name=eflora/><ref name=pacific/>

It has a hollow,<ref name=Lynch/> slender, 1<U+2013>3 branched stem, that grows up to between {{convert|50|-|120|cm|0|abbr=on}} long.<ref name=landscape/><ref name=bbc/><ref name=signa/><ref name=eflora/><ref name=cold/><ref name=rhs/><ref name=stebbings/><ref name=natural/><ref name=cassidy/><ref name=ClaireAustin/><ref name=american/><ref name=pacificsummary/><ref name=perennials/><ref name=European/><ref name=pacific/><ref name=russia/> 
The stems bear 2-5 (normally three) flowers, at the terminal ends between late spring and early summer, between May and June.<ref name=landscape/><ref name=bbc/><ref name=eflora/><ref name=rhs/><ref name=stebbings/><ref name=natural/><ref name=cassidy/><ref name=ClaireAustin/><ref name=perennials/><ref name=dailymail/><ref name=pacific/><ref name=russia/>

It has 3 brown paper-like [[spathe]]s (leaves of the flower bud), that are reddish at the base, measuring between {{convert|3|-|5|cm|0|abbr=on}} long.<ref name=eflora/><ref name=European/><ref name=handbook/><ref name=russia/>

The flowers come in a range of blue shades.<ref name=handbook/> From violet-blue,<ref name=bbc/><ref name=signa/><ref name=eflora/><ref name=cold/><ref name=rhs/><ref name=stebbings/><ref name=cassidy/><ref name=pacificsummary/><ref name=perennials/><ref name=European/><ref name=pacific/> to blue,<ref name=landscape/><ref name=ClaireAustin/><ref name=american/><ref name=European/> and occasionally white.<ref name=landscape/><ref name=signa/><ref name=stebbings/><ref name=cassidy/><ref name=ClaireAustin/><ref name=pacificsummary/><ref name=perennials/><ref name=pacific/><ref name=handbook/> The flowers are {{convert|6|-|7|cm|0|abbr=on}} in diameter.<ref name=landscape/><ref name=rhs/><ref name=stebbings/><ref name=European/>

It has 2 pairs of petals, 3 large [[sepals]] (outer petals), known as the 'falls' and 3 inner, smaller petals (or [[tepals]], known as the 'standards'.<ref name=growing/>
The drooping obovate falls, measuring 5-7.5&nbsp;cm long and 2<U+2013>2.5&nbsp;cm wide, have a wide (or flaring) white blade or signal (central part of the petal) with dark-blue to violet veining.<ref name=eflora/><ref name=rhs/><ref name=stebbings/><ref name=cassidy/><ref name=ClaireAustin/><ref name=European/><ref name=handbook/> The white forms of the iris have a tinge of lavender and dark veining.<ref name=handbook/>

The smaller narrow upright standards are between 4.5<U+2013>5.5&nbsp;cm long and 1.5<U+2013>1.8&nbsp;cm wide.<ref name=eflora/><ref name=ClaireAustin/><ref name=European/><ref name=russia/>

It has a light to dark blue-violet, circular perianth tube, about 1&nbsp;cm long, pale blue style (about 4<U+2013>5&nbsp;cm long), a pedicel between 1<U+2013>15&nbsp;cm long and a 1.5<U+2013>2&nbsp;cm roundly triangular, ovary.<ref name=eflora/><ref name=handbook/><ref name=russia/>

After the iris has flowered, it produces a short stubby seed capsule,<ref name=stebbings/><ref name=cassidy/> which is roundly triangular with low ridges at angles, measuring 3-4.5&nbsp;cm by 1-1.3&nbsp;cm.<ref name=eflora/><ref name=handbook/><ref name=russia/> Inside the capsule, are 2 rows of seeds, which are thin, flat, shaped like a capital D and dark brown seeds, measuring about 5&nbsp;mm by 3&nbsp;mm.<ref name=eflora/><ref name=handbook/>

==Native==
[[File:Eriskirch-EriskircherRied3-Asio.JPG|thumb|Iris sibirica growing in the grasslands of Germany]]
Iris sibirica is [[native plant|native]] to [[temperate]] areas between [[Europe]] and [[Central Asia]].<ref name=grin/><ref name=eflora/><ref name=rhs/><ref name=growing/> It has the widest distribution range of all the siberian iris series.<ref name=stebbings/>

===Range===
Within Europe,<ref name=landscape/><ref name=signa/><ref name=stebbings/><ref name=countryfile/><ref name=cassidy/><ref name=ClaireAustin/><ref name=European/> it is found in west [[France]],<ref name=perennials/> [[Italy]],<ref name=signa/><ref name=pacific/> [[Switzerland]],<ref name=perennials/><ref  name=russia/> [[Austria]],<ref  name=russia/> [[Czechoslovakia]],<ref name=kew/>  [[Germany]], [[Hungary]],<ref name=kew/> Poland, [[Romania]], [[Bulgaria]],<ref name=perennials/> Former [[Yugoslavia]],<ref name=perennials/> [[Belarus]], [[Estonia]], [[Latvia]], [[Lithuania]], [[Moldova]], [[Ukraine]]<ref name=kew/> and northern [[Turkey]].<ref name=grin/><ref name=signa/><ref name=countryfile/><ref name=cassidy/><ref name=ClaireAustin/><ref name=perennials/>

It is found in the [[Caucasus]] regions of [[Armenia]], [[Azerbaijan]] and [[Siberia]] (of the [[Russia|Russia Federation]]).<ref name=grin/> East to [[Lake Baikal]] (in Siberia).<ref name=landscape/><ref name=signa/><ref name=countryfile/><ref name=cassidy/><ref name=ClaireAustin/><ref name=perennials/><ref name=European/><ref name=pacific/><ref name=russia/>
      
It has been also [[Naturalisation (biology)|Naturalized]] in various states of North America. Including [[Ontario]] (in Canada), [[Connecticut]], [[Maine]], [[Massachusetts]], [[New York]], [[Pennsylvania]],
[[Virginia]] and [[California]].<ref name=grin/><ref name=eflora/>

===Habitat===
It is found growing in damp woodland,<ref name=kew/><ref name=natural/><ref name=parkes/><ref  name=russia/> wet meadows, grasslands or pastures,<ref name=kew/><ref name=natural/><ref name=parkes/><ref name=growing/><ref  name=russia/> reed swamps by lakes, and beside streams.<ref name=countryfile/><ref name=perennials/> They generally gain a lot of moisture from snow-melt of mountains, flooding streams and soaking areas beside them.<ref name=growing/>

Within North Amercia, it is found in the damp ditches beside roadsides.<ref name=eflora/>

===Status===
According to [[IUCN Red List]] criteria, it is 'Vulnerable' (VU) (in Czech Republic, Hungary, Ukraine) and it has become 'Extinct' in the Wild (EW) ([[Slovakia]]). It is considered to be rare and endangered in Poland and not considered threatened in Romania.<ref name=kew/>

==Hybrids and cultivars==
[[File:Iris sibirica 05.jpg|thumb|Close-up of the flower of Iris sibirica cultivar 'Summer Sky']]
Since the 1970s, hybridizers and plant breeders have been cross-pollinating the various species in the Siberian group with ''Iris sibirica'' to create many [[Hybrid (biology)|hybrids]].<ref name=cold/><ref name=RHSAZ>{{cite book|title=RHS A-Z encyclopedia of garden plants|year=2008|publisher=Dorling Kindersley|location=United Kingdom|isbn=1405332964|pages=1136}}</ref> Whose parentage is now so complicated that the cultivars, are no longer listed with a species name. Several hundred Siberian iris cultivars are registered with the American Iris Society.<ref name=dyingpotential/>
The flowers of the cultivars varying in colour from white to shades of blue or deep violet-blue.<ref name=European/><ref name=knowhow/>
Pale blue forms were originally obtained by crossing the white and the blue varieties of ''Iris sibirica'' , it also combines readily with ''Iris sanguinea'' to produce hybrids with the taller stems.<ref name=handbook/>
The flowers of hybrids can have arched, semi-flaring, flaring or overlapped falls; some of them even have ruffled or extra falls. The newer Japanese hybrids, have six pendant falls, which make them similar in appearance to the Japanese Iris or ''[[Iris ensata]]''.<ref name=parkes/>

Known Iris sibirica cultivars include;
'Acuta' ; 'Alba Grandiflora' ; 'Band of Angels';<ref name=cold/> 'Butter and Sugar' (white petals on top with yellow falls);<ref name=cold/><ref name=sissinghurst/><ref name=dailymail/><ref name=knowhow/> 'Caesar's Brother';<ref name=cold/> 'Caesar's Ghost' ; 'Cambridge' (created in 1964<ref name=dyingpotential/>);<ref name=perennials/> 'Coronation Anthem';<ref name=cold/> 'Dancing Nanou';<ref name=cold/> 'Dewful';<ref name=cold/> 'Dreaming Spires' (created in 1964<ref name=dyingpotential/>);<ref name=cold/> 'Ego' (a rich blue);<ref name=cold/><ref name=perennials/><ref name=dailymail/> 'Elmeney' ; 'Enid Burgoyne' ; 'Ewen';<ref name=cold/><ref name=perennials/> 'Flight Of Butterflies';<ref name=cold/><ref name=sissinghurst/><ref name=perennials/> 'Forward And Back' ; 'Grandis' ; 'Heavenly Blue';<ref name=pacific/> <U+2018>King of Kings<U+2019> (white blossoms);<ref name=knowhow/>  'Lactea' ; 'Leucantha'; 'Little Blue Sparkler' ; 'Mongolius' ; <U+2018>Mysterious Monique<U+2019>;<ref name=sissinghurst/> 'Navy Blue';<ref name=pacific/> 'Nigrescens'; 'Niklasse'; 'Papillon' (pale blue);<ref name=countryfile/> 'Perry's Blue' (pale blue);<ref name=perennials/><ref name=dailymail/> <U+2018>Placid Waters<U+2019> (with lavender blue flowers);<ref name=sissinghurst/> 'Prairie In Bloom' ; 'Pritiazheniye' ; 'Royal Blue';<ref name=perennials/> 'Ruffled Violet';<ref name=perennials/> 'Ruffles Plus';<ref name=dailymail/> <U+2018>Savoir Faire<U+2019> (many deep blue flowers held above the dense narrow foliage);<ref name=bristol/><ref name=perennials/> 'Shaker's Prayer' ; 'Sibirica Alba'; 'Sibirica Albescens'; 'Sibirica Angustifolia' ; 'Sibirica Atropurpurea' ; 'Sibirica Baxteri' ; 'Sibirica Blue Bird' ; 'Sibirica 'Compacta' ; 'Sibirica Cristata' ; 'Sibirica Flore Pleno' ; 'Sibirica Gracilis' ; 'Sibirica Mrs. Perry' ; 'Sibirica Nana' ; 'Sibirica Nana Alba' ; 'Sibirica Papillon' ; 'Sibirica Snowdrift' ; 'Silver Edge';<ref name=perennials/> 'Sky Wings';<ref name=perennials/> 'Snow Prince' ; <U+2018>Snow White<U+2019>:(white tinged with yellow)<ref name=dailymail/> <U+2018>Southcombe White<U+2019>;<ref name=sissinghurst/> <U+2018>Sultan<U+2019>s Ruby<U+2019>  (deep magenta blooms);<ref name=knowhow/> 'Summer Sky';<ref name=gworld>{{cite web |title=Iris sibirica Summer Sky |url=http://www.gardenersworld.com/plants/iris-sibirica-summer-sky/869.html publisher=gardenersworld.com |accessdate=3 January 2015}}</ref> <U+2018>Super Ego<U+2019>;<ref name=germanica/> 'Swank';<ref name=parkes/> 'U.S.O.';  <U+2018>Violet Flare<U+2019>;<ref name=germanica/> <U+2018>Wing on Wing<U+2019> (white);<ref name=knowhow/> and 'Wisley White'.<ref name=american/>

The following [[cultivars]] of ''I. sibirica'' have gained the [[Royal Horticultural Society]]'s [[Award of Garden Merit]] (in the UK):-
*'Butter and Sugar'<ref>{{cite web|title=RHS Plant Selector - ''Iris'' 'Butter and Sugar'|url=http://apps.rhs.org.uk/plantselector/plant?plantid=3252|accessdate=25 June 2013}}</ref>
*'Cambridge'<ref>{{cite web|title=RHS Plant Selector - ''Iris'' 'Cambridge'|url=http://apps.rhs.org.uk/plantselector/plant?plantid=3253|accessdate=25 June 2013}}</ref>
*'Ruffled Velvet'<ref>{{cite web|title=RHS Plant Selector - ''Iris'' 'Ruffled Velvet'|url=http://apps.rhs.org.uk/plantselector/plant?plantid=5402|accessdate=25 June 2013}}</ref>
*'Silver Edge'<ref>{{cite web|title=RHS Plant Selector - ''Iris'' 'Silver Edge'|url=http://apps.rhs.org.uk/plantselector/plant?plantid=3274|accessdate=25 June 2013}}</ref>

Known Iris sibirica crosses; 
'Abitibi' ; 'Aindling Goldauge' ; 'Aindling Libelle' ; 'Aindling Morgenstimmung' ; 'Aindling Rohrsaenger' ; 'Banish Misfortune' ; 'Butterfly Fountain' ; 'Chaudiere' ; 'Chrysobirica' ; 'Chrysobirica Gloriosa' ; 'Chrysobirica Purpurea' ; 'Common Denominator' ; 'Cookley Blue' ; 'Foretell' ; 'Gatineau' ; 'Helicon' ; 'Hohe Warte' ; 'Kootenay' ; 'Lichterfeldius' ; 'Madawaska' ; 'Matane' ; 'Mauve Snowtop' ; 'Moonscape' ; 'Neidenstein' ; 'Ottawa' ; 'Rideau' ; 'Rimouski' ; 'Royal Californian' ; 'Pausback Sibtosa' ; 'Pembina' ; 'Pennywhistle' ; 'Pickanock' ; 'Salamander Crossing' ; 'Sarah Tiffney' ; 'Sibulleyanna' ; 'Soothsayer' ; 'Sporting Chance' ; 'Starsteps' ; 'Stilles Wasser' ; 'True Blue'; 'Vidtinky Nochi' ; 'Violet Wave' ; 'Weber's Spring Blues' and 'Zeta'.<ref name=american/>

